pouch boundary-line patch 0015 - poll() tag-dispatch for AF_UNIX socket fds

Phase 6 sub-chunk 16c-pre (pouch-poll-tag). Closes a gap from sub-
chunk 12 (pouch-sockets, P6-pouch-sockets): poll(2) was the only fd-
consuming syscall NOT given a pouch-tag dispatch shim.

The 0006-pouch-sockets.patch wired:
  - read()       (src/unistd/read.c)   tag dispatch added
  - write()      (src/unistd/write.c)  tag dispatch added
  - close()      (src/unistd/close.c)  tag dispatch added
  - getsockopt() (src/network/getsockopt.c) tag dispatch added

But poll() (src/select/poll.c) was left pristine. Tagged fds (>=
0x40000000 + slot) passed to poll(2) reach the kernel as out-of-
range fds; kernel/poll.c::poll_scan_one writes POLLNVAL into
revents. The idiomatic accept loop in stratumd's stm_stratumd_
accept_loop reads:

    int prc = poll(&pfd, 1, /*timeout_ms=*/200);
    ...
    if (pfd.revents & (POLLERR | POLLHUP | POLLNVAL)) break;

POLLNVAL trips that branch, the accept loop returns STM_EBACKEND,
stratumd's main returns 2, the process exits, and the parent
(joey)'s wait_pid for some other child returns stratumd's pid
instead -- the "wrong pid" extinction race chains all the way to
kernel extinction via kproc.wait_pid (unfiltered at v1.0).

This patch overrides src/select/poll.c with a tag-dispatch shim
that mirrors the read/write/close pattern:

  - Untagged fds:    pass through to SYS_poll unchanged (fast path
                     -- the common case for pipe/spoor/devfd polls
                     is zero-copy).
  - Tagged + ready:  translate slot's kernel_fd into a temporary
                     pollfd[] scratch array; call SYS_poll on the
                     scratch; copy revents back into the caller's
                     array. The caller's fds[].fd identifiers are
                     preserved so subsequent close(fds[i].fd) still
                     hits the pouch_sock_close path.
  - Tagged + FRESH/  put -1 into the scratch entry; the kernel's
    vacant slot:     poll_scan_one fast-paths fd < 0 to POLLNVAL,
                     which is the POSIX-correct surface for an
                     unconnected socket polled.

Stack-bounded scratch: PROC_HANDLE_MAX = 64 entries (~ 1 KiB). The
kernel rejects nfds > 64 at sys_poll_for_proc; the shim mirrors
the bound so the tagged-translation path doesn't need a heap
allocation that could trip pre-mallocng-init Procs.

Subsequent ppoll(), select(), pselect() do NOT need their own
dispatch shim because they route through poll() (see the 0005-
pouch-poll.patch rewrites).

The audit gap is documented as a v1.x lift in
audit_p6_pouch_sockets_closed_list.md; this patch closes it as
part of the stratumd-listen unblock.

Files modified: one.

  src/select/poll.c  Full rewrite. Strips the upstream "#ifdef
      SYS_poll / SYS_ppoll fallback" cascade (the 0005 patch
      already adds SYS_poll = 29 unconditionally), adds the
      tag-dispatch shape from above.

Invariants preserved:

  P-1 (no foreign syscall numbers): no new syscall calls.
  P-3 (no silently-wrong POSIX): the FRESH/vacant slot case
       returns POLLNVAL (POSIX-correct for "polled fd is invalid")
       rather than masking with a fake-ready or fake-error revents.
  P-4 (boundary-line discipline): the patch touches one lower-
       half wrapper file. No upper-half files modified.

Binding design: docs/POUCH-DESIGN.md sec 14 row 16c-pre. Reference:
docs/reference/78-pouch.md (the polling backend; to be updated
with the tag-dispatch addendum).

Test: stratumd's stm_stratumd_accept_loop now polls its tagged
listener fd correctly. The 200-ms poll cycles produce
revents == 0 (no waiting client) until joey's t_srv_connect
arrives, at which point revents == POLLIN; accept() returns the
kernel-minted Spoor fd; serve_client takes the connection.
Without this patch, the listener_fd's first poll returns POLLNVAL
and the loop bails -- the listen-bound success surfaces but
serving is impossible.

--- a/src/select/poll.c
+++ b/src/select/poll.c
@@ -1,20 +1,150 @@
+/* pouch boundary-line replacement for poll() (P6-pouch-stratumd-boot
+ * 16c-pre poll-tag-dispatch).
+ *
+ * Sub-chunk 12 (pouch-sockets) wired read / write / close / getsockopt
+ * to translate pouch-tagged socket fds to their kernel handles via
+ * pouch_sock_kernel_fd before crossing the syscall seam. poll(2) was
+ * left pristine -- passing a tagged fd to SYS_poll causes the kernel
+ * to see fd >= 0x40000000 (above PROC_HANDLE_MAX = 64), handle_get
+ * fails, kernel/poll.c::poll_scan_one writes POLLNVAL into revents,
+ * and the caller's `if (revents & (POLLERR|POLLHUP|POLLNVAL)) break`
+ * idiom (used by stratumd's stm_stratumd_accept_loop and any other
+ * pollable-listener consumer) bails immediately.
+ *
+ * This shim mirrors the read/write dispatch shape: for any tagged fd
+ * in the input pollfd[] array, look up the slot's kernel handle and
+ * pass THAT to SYS_poll. Untagged fds pass through unchanged. The
+ * caller's fd identifiers are preserved across the call -- the
+ * translation lives in a stack-bounded scratch array.
+ *
+ *   tagged LISTENING/CONNECTED slot -> kernel_fd (a valid Spoor/Srv
+ *                                       handle in [0, PROC_HANDLE_MAX))
+ *   tagged FRESH slot              -> -1 in the kfds[i] entry (kernel's
+ *                                       poll_scan_one fast-paths fd<0 to
+ *                                       POLLNVAL, the correct POSIX
+ *                                       answer for an unconnected socket)
+ *   tagged but unallocated slot    -> -1 in the kfds[i] entry (same:
+ *                                       POLLNVAL surfaces the EBADF
+ *                                       state without entering the
+ *                                       kernel with a bogus fd value)
+ *
+ * Stack-bounded scratch: PROC_HANDLE_MAX = 64 entries (~ 1 KiB).
+ * nfds > 64 returns -EINVAL pre-syscall (the kernel rejects the same
+ * shape; the shim mirrors the bound so the tagged-translation path
+ * doesn't need a heap allocation that pre-mallocng-init Procs would
+ * trip on).
+ *
+ * Fast path: when no tagged fd is present, the original pristine
+ * shape is preserved -- SYS_poll runs against the caller's array
+ * directly with zero copy overhead.
+ *
+ * Reference: docs/POUCH-DESIGN.md sec 14 row 16c-pre, 0015-pouch-
+ * poll-tag.patch. */
 #include <poll.h>
 #include <time.h>
 #include <signal.h>
+#include <errno.h>
+#include <stddef.h>
 #include "syscall.h"
+#include "_pouch_socket.h"

+/* Mirrors kernel/include/thylacine/proc.h PROC_HANDLE_MAX. The kernel
+ * already rejects nfds > 64 at sys_poll_for_proc; we mirror to bound
+ * the stack allocation. */
+#define POUCH_POLL_NFDS_MAX 64u
+
 int poll(struct pollfd *fds, nfds_t n, int timeout)
 {
-#ifdef SYS_poll
-	return syscall_cp(SYS_poll, fds, n, timeout);
-#else
-#if SYS_ppoll_time64 == SYS_ppoll
-	typedef long long ppoll_ts_t[2];
-#else
-	typedef long ppoll_ts_t[2];
-#endif
-	return syscall_cp(SYS_ppoll, fds, n, timeout>=0 ?
-		((ppoll_ts_t){ timeout/1000, timeout%1000*1000000 }) : 0,
-		0, _NSIG/8);
-#endif
+	/* Zero fds: the kernel rejects nfds == 0, so we cannot pass it through.
+	 * A nonblocking probe over no fds is immediately "nothing ready" (0); a
+	 * timed or indefinite wait over no fds has no zero-fd kernel sleep surface
+	 * at v1.0 (ENOSYS, matching 0005 select()). RND2-F1. */
+	if (n == 0) {
+		if (timeout == 0) {
+			return 0;
+		}
+		errno = ENOSYS;
+		return -1;
+	}
+	if (!fds) {
+		errno = EFAULT;
+		return -1;
+	}
+	if (n > POUCH_POLL_NFDS_MAX) {
+		errno = EINVAL;
+		return -1;
+	}
+
+	/* Fast path: if no tagged fd is present, run against the caller's
+	 * array directly (zero copy). Most pouch programs poll only on
+	 * pipe fds / spoor handles / etc; the tagged-socket case is
+	 * specific to AF_UNIX SOCK_STREAM consumers. */
+	/* A negative fd is POSIX-ignored (revents := 0, not polled). It must
+	 * also force the slow path: the fast path would hand it to the kernel,
+	 * which returns POLLNVAL for fd < 0 (counted ready), defeating the
+	 * timeout and busy-spinning the caller. A tagged fd needs translation
+	 * (R5-F3). */
+	int needs_slow = 0;
+	for (nfds_t i = 0; i < n; i++) {
+		if (fds[i].fd < 0 || (fds[i].fd & POUCH_SOCK_TAG) != 0) {
+			needs_slow = 1;
+			break;
+		}
+	}
+	if (!needs_slow) {
+		return syscall_cp(SYS_poll, fds, n, timeout);
+	}
+
+	/* Compact the active (fd >= 0) entries into kfds, translating tagged
+	 * sockets; map[] records each kept entry's original index. A negative fd
+	 * is EXCLUDED from the kernel array entirely (not merely set to -1) so it
+	 * cannot make the kernel return immediately -- only the live fds drive
+	 * the blocking poll, and the ignored entry reads revents 0. */
+	struct pollfd kfds[POUCH_POLL_NFDS_MAX];
+	nfds_t map[POUCH_POLL_NFDS_MAX];
+	nfds_t nk = 0;
+	for (nfds_t i = 0; i < n; i++) {
+		if (fds[i].fd < 0) {
+			fds[i].revents = 0;
+			continue;
+		}
+		int kfd;
+		if ((fds[i].fd & POUCH_SOCK_TAG) != 0) {
+			kfd = pouch_sock_kernel_fd(fds[i].fd);
+			/* FRESH/vacant tagged slot is a genuinely-invalid fd:
+			 * keep it (kfd = -1) so the kernel reports POLLNVAL, the
+			 * POSIX EBADF surface. Unlike a caller-disabled negative
+			 * fd, this is a real error the caller must see. */
+			if (kfd < 0) kfd = -1;
+		} else {
+			kfd = fds[i].fd;
+		}
+		kfds[nk].fd      = kfd;
+		kfds[nk].events  = fds[i].events;
+		kfds[nk].revents = 0;
+		map[nk] = i;
+		nk++;
+	}
+
+	if (nk == 0) {
+		/* Every entry was a POSIX-ignored negative fd. Same as the n == 0
+		 * case above: the kernel rejects nfds == 0, so do NOT pass through
+		 * (RND2-F1). Nonblocking -> 0; timed/indefinite -> ENOSYS. */
+		if (timeout == 0) {
+			return 0;
+		}
+		errno = ENOSYS;
+		return -1;
+	}
+
+	int r = syscall_cp(SYS_poll, kfds, nk, timeout);
+
+	/* Map revents back (fd left untouched so the caller still sees its
+	 * original tagged identifiers). Ignored fd < 0 entries already read
+	 * revents 0 from the build loop. */
+	for (nfds_t k = 0; k < nk; k++) {
+		fds[map[k]].revents = kfds[k].revents;
+	}
+
+	return r;
 }
